<td valign=top colspan=3><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" > 
<a target=_blank HREF=http://www.makingwavesaudio.com><u>Making Waves Audio</u></a><br><I>Review by Johan Lundin</I><br><br>Making Waves Audio is a great DJ sequencer program. If Making Waves had the intention to compete with E-Jay they have succeeded. For those of you who have used E-Jay for making music or remixes, and have been frustrated of the limitations you run across, Making Waves Audio will offer you all those things you lacked and more. Making Waves Audio (MWA) is very easy to get started with since it uses a simple idea of tracks (sequences) and bars, like any other sequencer, and you get a nice overview at all times over the complete song that you are working with.<br><br><img src="/bilder/mwa1.gif"><br><br>A track can be defined with different types of functions. Basically you can choose a track to contain either a sound or an effect. If you assign a sound to a track you can treat the sound as a single sound (good for remixes, sounds effect or speech), percussion (if you want to edit the track like a drum machine) or you can choose to use the track as notes (e.g. if you easily want to lay down that fat base). If you choose a track to be an effect track, then you have a lot of effects to choose from.<br><br>Among the effects you can choose for a track is: compressor, delay, distortion, expander, harmoniser, filter, flanger, modulator, pitch shift, reverb, reverse, stereo and a lot of note transformation effects e.g. attack, length and slide. The effects are really good and you get total control over the effects when you lay them down in the song. You can actually change the appearance of an effect for each note you play (of course you say) but MWA lets you just click and draw to do this. It can&#8217;t get any easier than this! Also I haven&#8217;t emphasized on the really cool effects. Imagine just having a boring monotone baseline running over and over again. You know you would like to do something with the bass but you can&#8217;t figure out what. Now you just add a little distortion or modulation to the track and maybe some other cool effect and then suddenly you have created an intense sound.<br><br><img src="/bilder/mwa2.gif"><br><br>After you have constructed a couple of tracks you would want to put them together into a song. This is extremely easy since you only have to klick out the tracks into the song matrix. You have total control over the song at all times! Finally when you are satisfied with you song and you want to put it on the CD, you just push the &#8220;copy song to sample file&#8221; button and MWA will create a wav-file of the complete song for you.<br><br>MWA has a lot of other features that are not brought up here in this short review, but I can really recommend that you take a look at this program if you like working with samples and remixes. MWA is not a normal sequencer in the sense that you have a lot of midi instruments connected to you computer that are controlled by the sequencer. However, if you don&#8217;t own a lot of instruments or just like to work with only samples MWA is the perfect choice! There are of course a zillion ways to use this program. Even if you do own a bunch of instruments you would have to put your recordings into digital format sooner or later if you want to have your music on a CD. You could then use MWA just to do the final editing of your song or make a couple of remixes very easily. The way I use MWA for the moment being is to download new fresh samples from www.analoguesamples.com, make a cool drumtrack, add the bass and just rock on!<br><br>Johan Lundin<br> </font></td>
